{
  "answer": "**In Mirza Ghalib's ghazal \"Chashm-e-khoobaan khaamoshi mein bhi nawa-pardaaz hai,\"** the lover's form is a \"tuneless instrument\" (*saaz-e-taale'-e-na-saaz*), and their *naala*—that raw, piercing wail—is explicitly its sound, likened to the revolution of celestial bodies (*gardish-e-sayyaara ki aawaaz*):[^1]\n\n> **Transliteration:**  \n> Paikar-e-ushaaq saaz-e-taale'-e-na-saaz hai  \n> *Naala* goya gardish-e-sayyaara ki aawaaz hai  \n> \n> **Translation:**  \n> The lover's body, tuned to fate's disgrace;  \n> His cry, the sound of planets whirling space.[^1]\n\nThe audible quality of *naala* is central here: it's not just emotional content but a resonant, cosmic *aawaaz* (sound)—prolonged, throaty, echoing like orbital grind or hum, evoking the *naala*'s phonetic drag (naa-laa, nasal and drawn-out). English translations like \"cry\" or \"lament\" flatten this to semantics; to recover the sonic dimension, it needs \"wail\"—or better, \"that throaty wail\" / \"drawn-out wail,\" with phonetic hints like \"naa-laa\" or descriptors (\"a grinding celestial moan\") to mimic its visceral, auditory immediacy.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/23-chashm-e-khoobaan-khaamoshi-mein-bhi-nawa-pardaaz-/translation/#p-6c867d).\n[^2]: The same ghazal later calls a caged bird's *naala-e-murgh-e-aseer* a *naghmah* (melody) in its own ears, reinforcing *naala*'s musical-wailing sonority: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/23-chashm-e-khoobaan-khaamoshi-mein-bhi-nawa-pardaaz-/translation/#p-536f41).",
